<?php die("Access Denied"); ?>#x#a:2:{s:6:"output";s:0:"";s:6:"result";a:3:{i:0;O:8:"stdClass":8:{s:22:"virtuemart_category_id";s:2:"13";s:13:"category_name";s:8:"PC Games";s:20:"category_description";s:0:"";s:8:"metadesc";s:0:"";s:7:"metakey";s:0:"";s:11:"customtitle";s:0:"";s:4:"slug";s:8:"pc-games";s:19:"virtuemart_media_id";a:1:{i:0;s:2:"33";}}i:1;O:8:"stdClass":8:{s:22:"virtuemart_category_id";s:2:"15";s:13:"category_name";s:14:"Play station 3";s:20:"category_description";s:6081:"<p style="margin: 0.5em 0px; line-height: inherit; color: #252525; font-family: sans-serif; font-size: 14px;">The <b>PlayStation 3</b> (abbreviated to <b>PS3</b>) is a <a style="color: #0b0080; background: none;" title="Home video game console" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Home_video_game_console">home video game console</a> developed by <a style="color: #0b0080; background: none;" title="Sony Interactive Entertainment" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sony_Interactive_Entertainment">Sony Interactive Entertainment</a>, formerly Sony Computer Entertainment. It is the successor to <a style="color: #0b0080; background: none;" title="PlayStation 2" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PlayStation_2">PlayStation 2</a>, and is part of the <a style="color: #0b0080; background: none;" title="PlayStation" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PlayStation">PlayStation brand of consoles</a>. It competed with <a style="color: #0b0080; background: none;" title="Microsoft" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microsoft">Microsoft</a>'s <a style="color: #0b0080; background: none;" title="Xbox 360" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xbox_360">Xbox 360</a> and <a style="color: #0b0080; background: none;" title="Nintendo" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nintendo">Nintendo</a>'s <a style="color: #0b0080; background: none;" title="Wii" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wii">Wii</a> as part of the <a class="mw-redirect" style="color: #0b0080; background: none;" title="History of video game consoles (seventh generation)" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_video_game_consoles_(seventh_generation)">seventh generation of video game consoles</a>. It was first released on November 11, 2006, in <a style="color: #0b0080; background: none;" title="Japan" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japan">Japan</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-Japandate_8-0" class="reference" style="line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;"><a style="color: #0b0080; background: none;" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PlayStation_3#cite_note-Japandate-8">[8]</a></sup> November 17, 2006 in <a style="color: #0b0080; background: none;" title="North America" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/North_America">North America</a>, and March 27, 2007 in <a style="color: #0b0080; background: none;" title="Europe" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Europe">Europe</a> and <a style="color: #0b0080; background: none;" title="Australia" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Australia">Australia</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-NAdate_9-0" class="reference" style="line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;"><a style="color: #0b0080; background: none;" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PlayStation_3#cite_note-NAdate-9">[9]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-PALlaunchdate_10-0" class="reference" style="line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;"><a style="color: #0b0080; background: none;" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PlayStation_3#cite_note-PALlaunchdate-10">[10]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-autogenerated2_11-0" class="reference" style="line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;"><a style="color: #0b0080; background: none;" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PlayStation_3#cite_note-autogenerated2-11">[11]</a></sup></p>&#13;&#10;<p style="margin: 0.5em 0px; line-height: inherit; color: #252525; font-family: sans-serif; font-size: 14px;">The console was first officially announced at <a style="color: #0b0080; background: none;" title="History of the Electronic Entertainment Expo" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_the_Electronic_Entertainment_Expo">E3 2005</a>, and was released at the end of 2006. It was the first console to use <a class="mw-redirect" style="color: #0b0080; background: none;" title="Blu-ray Disc" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blu-ray_Disc">Blu-ray Disc</a> as its primary storage medium.<sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference" style="line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;"><a style="color: #0b0080; background: none;" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PlayStation_3#cite_note-12">[12]</a></sup> The console was the first PlayStation to integrate social gaming services, included it being the first to introduce Sony's social gaming service, <a style="color: #0b0080; background: none;" title="PlayStation Network" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PlayStation_Network">PlayStation Network</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-US.PS.COM.PSN_13-0" class="reference" style="line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;"><a style="color: #0b0080; background: none;" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PlayStation_3#cite_note-US.PS.COM.PSN-13">[13]</a></sup> and its<sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference" style="line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;"><a style="color: #0b0080; background: none;" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PlayStation_3#cite_note-14">[14]</a></sup> remote connectivity with <a style="color: #0b0080; background: none;" title="PlayStation Portable" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PlayStation_Portable">PlayStation Portable</a>and <a style="color: #0b0080; background: none;" title="PlayStation Vita" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PlayStation_Vita">PlayStation Vita</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-15" class="reference" style="line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px;"><a style="color: #0b0080; background: none;" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PlayStation_3#cite_note-15">[15]</a></sup> being able to remote control the console from the devices. In September 2009, the <i>Slim</i> model of the PlayStation 3 was released, being lighter and thinner than the original version, which notably featured a redesigned logo and marketing design, as well as a minor start-up change in software. A <i>Super Slim</i> variation was then released in late 2012, further refining and redesigning the console</p>";s:8:"metadesc";s:0:"";s:7:"metakey";s:0:"";s:11:"customtitle";s:0:"";s:4:"slug";s:14:"play-station-3";s:19:"virtuemart_media_id";a:1:{i:0;s:2:"35";}}i:2;O:8:"stdClass":8:{s:22:"virtuemart_category_id";s:2:"14";s:13:"category_name";s:10:"Xbox Games";s:20:"category_description";s:0:"";s:8:"metadesc";s:0:"";s:7:"metakey";s:0:"";s:11:"customtitle";s:0:"";s:4:"slug";s:10:"xbox-games";s:19:"virtuemart_media_id";a:1:{i:0;s:2:"34";}}}}